Here are both approaches using Shell navigation and `IQueryAttributable`:

**1. Passing a simple string (product ID):**

```csharp
// Navigate from ProductListPage
await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"{nameof(ProductDetailsPage)}?productId={product.Id}");
```

**2. Passing a complex object:**

```csharp
var navParams = new Dictionary<string, object>
{
    { "product", selectedProduct }
};
await Shell.Current.GoToAsync(nameof(ProductDetailsPage), navParams);
```

**Receiving both in the ViewModel with `IQueryAttributable`:**

```csharp
public class ProductDetailsViewModel : ObservableObject, IQueryAttributable
{
    public void ApplyQueryAttributes(IDictionary<string, object> query)
    {
        // Approach 1: simple string parameter
        if (query.TryGetValue("productId", out var idObj))
        {
            string productId = idObj.ToString();
            // fetch product from service, etc.
            LoadProduct(productId);
        }

        // Approach 2: full object (passed via Dictionary<string, object>)
        if (query.TryGetValue("product", out var productObj) && productObj is Product product)
        {
            Name = product.Name;
            Price = product.Price;
            // use directly — no fetch needed
        }
    }
}
```

**Wire up the ViewModel as the page's `BindingContext`:**

```csharp
// ProductDetailsPage.xaml.cs
public ProductDetailsPage(ProductDetailsViewModel vm)
{
    InitializeComponent();
    BindingContext = vm;
}
```

**Key differences:**

| | String param | Object param |
|---|---|---|
| **Syntax** | `GoToAsync("Page?key=val")` | `GoToAsync("Page", dict)` |
| **Received as** | `object` (cast/`.ToString()`) | Original type (cast with `is`) |
| **Survives URI** | Yes (serializable) | No (in-memory only) |
| **Use when** | Simple IDs, flags | Full model, avoiding re-fetch |

Both approaches land in the same `ApplyQueryAttributes` method, so you can support either caller pattern from one ViewModel.
